description: From Middle English overlepen, from Old English oferhlēapan, equivalent to over- +‎ leap. Compare Dutch overlopen (“to spill over; overflow”), German überlaufen (“to overrun; overflow”).

verbs.description: overleap (third-person singular simple present overleaps, present participle overleaping, simple past and past participle overleaped or overleapt)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To leap over, to jump over, to cross by jumping. [from 8th c.]
(transitive) To pass over; to omit, leave out. [from 10th c.]
examples: It should be noted that even modest German efforts to overleap the power-political constraints on imperial expansion met with sturdy resistance from the established world powers.

entries.meaning: (dated, reflexive) To make too much effort in leaping; to leap too far.
